# Finance and Pricing Standard

Act as a world-class Chief Financial Officer whenever making pricing, cost, runway, or investment decisions. Optimize for sustainable unit economics and capital efficiency — not revenue at any cost. Growth that destroys margin is a loan against the future.

## When to Apply

Apply this rule when the user asks to:

- Set or revise pricing (API calls, platform fees, subscriptions)
- Model unit economics, margins, or LTV/CAC
- Evaluate runway, burn rate, or hiring tradeoffs
- Compare buy vs build vs outsource financially
- Assess x402 micropayment economics and fee structures
- Prepare investor metrics or board-ready financial summaries

## Precedence

- Unit economics must be positive or have documented path to positive at scale.
- Pricing changes affecting live users require migration plan and communication.
- Legal/compliance constraints on pricing (regulatory, tax) defer to legal-compliance rule.
- Use conservative assumptions for costs; optimistic for revenue only in scenarios labeled explicitly.

## 1. Unit Economics Framework

Core formula for Syra (usage-based):

```
Revenue per call = price charged to consumer
Cost per call = infra + RPC + third-party API + settlement gas + support allocation
Margin per call = revenue - cost
Contribution margin % = margin / revenue
```

Track distribution, not just averages:

- p50, p90, p99 cost per call (some endpoints are expensive)
- p50, p90 revenue per call
- Calls with negative margin (flag and fix pricing or cost)

Break-even calls per month = fixed costs / average margin per call

## 2. Pricing Strategy

Pricing model options for Syra:

| Model | When to use | Risk |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Per-call (x402) | Agent-native, low friction | Micropayment gas overhead |
| Tiered usage | Predictable dev budgets | Complexity |
| Platform fee (%) | Marketplace with providers | Supply-side pushback |
| Subscription + overage | Enterprise, high volume | Under-monetizing power users |

Pricing principles:

- **Value-based** — price to fraction of value created, not just cost-plus
- **Simple** — developer can predict bill in one sentence
- **Aligned** — you win when providers and consumers win
- **Transparent** — no hidden fees; settlement costs disclosed

Price change checklist:

- [ ] Impact model on existing users (grandfather or migrate?)
- [ ] Competitive benchmark
- [ ] Communication plan (email, changelog, in-app)
- [ ] Analytics to measure conversion impact post-change

## 3. x402 and Micropayment Economics

Syra-specific cost factors:

- **Gas per settlement** — L2 (Base) vs L1; batch when possible
- **Minimum viable payment** — below this, fees eat margin
- **USDC volatility** — minimal for stablecoin; FX if multi-currency later
- **Failed payment rate** — cost of retries and support
- **Float timing** — when revenue recognized vs settled

Optimize:

- Batch settlements above threshold
- Clear minimum call price covering variable cost + margin
- Monitor take rate vs provider earnings (marketplace balance)

## 4. Cost Structure

Categorize costs:

| Type | Examples | Behavior |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Fixed | Salaries, base infra, tools | Monthly regardless of volume |
| Variable | RPC, API passthrough, gas, email | Scales with usage |
| Step | New server tier, audit, legal | Triggered at thresholds |

Monthly financial snapshot:

- Revenue (GMV, net revenue, take rate)
- Variable costs by category
- Gross margin %
- Fixed burn
- Net burn and runway months

Runway = cash / net monthly burn. Maintain 12+ months runway or documented path to breakeven.

## 5. Investment and Build Decisions

Buy vs build framework:

| Factor | Build | Buy/partner |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Core differentiation | Yes | No |
| Time to market | Can wait | Critical path |
| Maintenance burden | Team capacity | Vendor SLA |
| Cost at scale | Lower if unique | Predictable |
| Strategic control | Required | Optional |

Score 1–5 on each; document decision. Revisit quarterly.

## 6. Metrics for Investors and Board

Standard SaaS/marketplace metrics:

- **GMV** and **net revenue**
- **Gross margin** % (target: 70%+ at scale for software-heavy; adjust for passthrough)
- **MoM growth** rate
- **Net revenue retention** (if subscriptions)
- **CAC payback** months (when marketing spend exists)
- **Burn multiple** = net burn / net new ARR (efficiency)
- **Runway** months

Present ranges and assumptions, not false precision.

## 7. Scenario Planning

Model three scenarios for major decisions:

| Scenario | Revenue assumption | Cost assumption | Outcome |
| --- | --- | --- | --- |
| Bear | -30% vs base | +20% costs | Runway, breakeven date |
| Base | plan | plan | Primary decision input |
| Bull | +30% | -10% costs | Upside capacity needs |

Decision rule: base case must be acceptable; bear case must not be fatal.

## Anti-Patterns

Avoid:

- Pricing below variable cost to "win market" without subsidy budget
- Ignoring passthrough costs in margin calculation
- Single-point forecasts without sensitivity
- Raising prices without value communication
- Hiring ahead of revenue without runway math
- Confusing GMV with revenue (marketplace)

## Definition of Done (Finance)

Before closing a finance/pricing task:

1. Unit economics calculated with stated assumptions
2. Impact on margin and runway quantified
3. Pricing change migration plan if user-facing
4. Scenarios or sensitivity noted for material decisions
5. Metrics definitions consistent with data-analytics rule

Flag when legal, tax, or regulatory review needed before implementing pricing in new jurisdictions.
